<span id="freeTextContainer13482427010930256019">On July 1st, 1863 the Battle of Gettysburg began. The first day is overlooked by the other events of the battle that occurred on days 2 and 3, and the movie portrays it as a small engagement, but the first day of Gettysburg was a critical day for both sides. Some would argue it was the day that decided the battle. <br/><br/>Harry Pfanz was a former park ranger at Gettysburg and he wrote three volumes of the battle. Personally, I thought his day 1 book was the best of the three. This book really gave the f</span>
  <span id="freeText13482427010930256019" style="display:none">On July 1st, 1863 the Battle of Gettysburg began. The first day is overlooked by the other events of the battle that occurred on days 2 and 3, and the movie portrays it as a small engagement, but the first day of Gettysburg was a critical day for both sides. Some would argue it was the day that decided the battle. <br /><br />Harry Pfanz was a former park ranger at Gettysburg and he wrote three volumes of the battle. Personally, I thought his day 1 book was the best of the three. This book really gave the first day the justice it rightfully deserves. He also dispels a lot of rumors. One is that Meade believed if Gettysburg were captured by the Gettysburg that was bad for the Union. However, as Pfanz noted, Meade did not want to fight originally and had his Pipe Creek Plan, a way to have Lee fight him at a strong position in Maryland. <br /><br />If want a detailed book about the Battle of Gettysburg, this is the book that you should read. The battle description of the first day is remarkable. If you want a lighter and overall detail of the battle, Stephen Sears and Noah Trudeau's books are better suited. </span>
  <a data-text-id="13482427010930256019" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

